Ask HN: Am I wrong to think this is disrespectful?
text:
I have been working on a startup idea for about year, talking to potential customers, refining the technical roadmap based on market feedback. On advice of a few friends that I need to thinking about funding now, not 6 months down the roads, I aligned the meeting with a couple of investors. Now comes a twist.

A friend of mine was terminated from his job, and I had aspirations to invite him as a cofounder. He contacted me one day before the intro call with investor, and I said, we will think about your situations but right now I am building this pitch deck. He offered to help. (He has been helpful in the past), So I handed over the last two slides to him.

He added another slide with the team intros and added him as cofounder & CEO. Although, if things worked out, He was my number 1 cofounder choice, but I feel this is disrespectful. He just cannot write CEO without asking me first. This shows a lack of respect, and I am not really sure if I want to work with his guy.

Need second opinions.

title: Show HN: I made an interactive stock watchlist maker
text:
Hi HN, I’m Brian, the maker behind Dollarsign. Over the pandemic I've done a lot of financial research and I wanted a tool to help collect it and automatically generate watchlists. This site is a side-project for that. It uses 15-min delayed data from all markets along with live news. Since there are other people probably thinking similar things as your own ideas, there's also the ability to fork, watch and star watchlists in a github-like fashion.

Let me know what you think.

You can jump directly to making watchlists here: https://app.dollarsign.ai/w/new

Cheers!

[edit] fixed terms/privacy/disclaimer links on www page.

Ask HN: How to find an in-office tech job
text:
I'm an experienced (10+ years) software engineer in the Bay Area. It's getting to be time to change jobs, but unlike most my peers (and my team), I prefer working in the office with my team in-person.

With so many companies going remote-first, I'm not sure how to find a local company where most of my colleagues will be in the office most days any more. Where should I look?

P.s.: I'm not looking for a remote vs. in-person debate. Many, many threads here have gone over the pros and cons, it's getting tiresome, and I know which is right for me.
